results.name: a(n) = number of numbers k <= sigma(n) such that k is not equal to sigma(d) for any divisor d of n, where sigma = A000203.
comment: Sequence is not the same as A065608(n): a(66) = 137, A065608(66) = 136.
link: Antti Karttunen, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
example: For n = 4, sigma(4) = 7, from numbers 1 - 7 there are four numbers k such that k is not equal to sigma(d) for any divisor d of n: 2, 4, 5, 6; a(4) = 4.
mathematica: f[n_] := Block[{c = 0, k = 1, lmt = DivisorSigma[1, n] + 1, sd = DivisorSigma[1, #] & /@ Divisors@ n}, While[k < lmt, If[! MemberQ[sd, k], c++]; k++]; c]; Array[f, 67]
